title: Ruins of the Puget Sound National Bank, June 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph. "Fire. June 6, 1889. Ruins. Puget Sound National Bank. Front Street [1st Ave.] and James Street."

title: Yesler House, ca. 1859
description: Transcribed from photograph. "Houses. Henry L. Yesler house at Front and James Street. About 1861. Hillory Butler house at back right."

title: Barbeque enclosure for Henry Villard's visit, September 12, 1883
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Villard, Henry. Visit. September 12, 1883. Barbecue enclosure on Territorial University grounds, between Seneca Street and Union Street. From Third Avenue to Fifth Avenue, where the first potlatch was held."

title: View from Beacon Hill looking north, ca. 1885
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Beacon Hill 1880. Looking North. 1. Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad bridge. 2. Jackson Street Bridge. 3. Main Street Bridge. 4. Academy of the Holy Names."
intersection: 10th Ave. S. and S. Dearborn St.

title: Squire's Opera House, 1880
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Theaters. Squire's Opera House. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.] between Washington Street and Main Street. Built 1876. Destroyed by fire June 6, 1889. 1880." Transcribed from back of photograph:  "1. Clancy's Saloon. 2. Jake Levy, pawn broker. 3. Klein and Rosenberg; McNaught,  McNaught and Mitchel, lawyers. 4. Hotel Brunswick and Squire's Opera House. 5. Stowell and Co., druggists, Max Heiber, tailor. 6. A. P. Hotaling, wholesale liquor dealer."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St.

title: Engine Company No. 1., July 23, 1883
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Portraits. Group. Engine Co. No. 1. Volunteer fire department. July 25, 1883. 1. Joe Keppler. 2. Will Perry. 2. Lizzie McDonald. 4. Oscar Krieg. 5. John Storm. 6. Al Cutlar. Charles McDonald house in background."

title: View From Denny Hill, 1882
description: Views. From Denny Hill looking East. 1882. 1. Otto Ranke house. 2. Harry Bigelow house.

title: 1st Ave. and Yesler Way decorations for Henry Villard visit, September 14, 1883
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Villard, Henry. Visit. September 14, 1883. Decorations on Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.] at Mill Street [Yesler Way]. 1. Gem Saloon. 2. Gardner Kellogg Drug Store. 3. Z. C. Miles Hardware store." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Gem Saloon. Gard. Kellogg's drug store. Head of Street--Z. C. Miles stoves, etc. Yesler Leary Block in dim distance."

title: Steamer "Ohio" at Pier 5, 1913
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Ships. Ohio (Steamer) 1913. At Pier 5, foot of Seneca Street. On Alaska run."

title: View From King St., 1878
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Views. From King Street. 1878. Looking North. 1. Felker house. 2. Carkeek house. 3. Arlington Hotel. 4. Squire's Opera House and New Brunswick Hotel." Transcribed from back of photograph: "R. Carkeek's home, Arlington Hotel, Squire's Opera House and New Brunswick Hotel. Center foreground-Felker Home."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. King St.

title: 1st Ave. and Yesler Way decorations for President Benjamin Harrison's visit, May 5, 1891
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Harrison, Benjamin. Visit. May 6, 1891. Decorations on building. Yesler Avenue and Front Street. 1. Hotel Northern. 2. Gatzert Building. 3. National Bank of Commerce. 4. First National Bank." Transcribed from back of photograph: "President Harrison in Seattle, lower left. Occidental, lower right."

title: 1st Ave. S. between S. Washington St. and S. Main St., 1870
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. 1870. East side between Washington Street and Main Street. On verso:  Pinkham's Variety store, Levy's Pawn shop, Eureka Bakery. Wyckoff home (with veranda) S. E. corner of Second Avenue and Cherry Street. Dick Atkins home (above that)." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Pinkham's Variety Store, Levy's Pawn Shop, Eureka Bakery. Wyckoff home (with verandah), S. E. corner of Second and Cherry. Dick Atkins home (above). J. M. Colman's home above that."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St.

title: View north on 1st Ave. from Cherry St., July 4, 1888
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Front Street looking North from Cherry Street to Columbia Street. July 4, 1888. Parade. 1. Safe Deposit Building- Merchant's National Bank, Albert Forrest, dentist. 2. Poncin Building: Treen & Raymond, boots and shoes, James A. Carey & Co. insurance. 3. Union Block- G. Davies, bookseller,  C. C. Calkins, real estate. 4. Toklas, Singerman & Co. (later McDougall & Southwick Co." 5. Colman Row (across Columbia)."
subjects: Seattle Safe Deposit and Trust Company
James A. Carey and Company (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Territorial University decorated for Henry Villard visit, September 14, 1883
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Villard, Henry. Visit. September 14, 1883. Territorial University decorations."

title: View north from 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St., 1874
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. 1874 looking North from Main Street. 1. New England house. 2. Arlington Hotel."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: View NW on 1st Ave. S. from S. Main St., 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. 1870. Looking northwest.  Buildings--1. W. A. Jenning's store. 2. San Francisco store. 3. L. A. Treen store. Men--2. Unidentified. 2. George Reynolds. 3. Perry Parsons. 4. Jesse George. 5. Unidentified. 6. Melody choir (Melchoir)."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: Yesler House at 1st Ave. and James St., ca. 1883
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Houses. Yesler, Henry. Left side:  House at Front Street (First Avenue and James Street). About 1883. Mr. and Mrs. Yesler standing on corner."

title: View north from 1st Ave. and Seneca St., 1913
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. First Avenue. 1913. Looking North from Seneca Street. 1. Amos Brown house. 2. Hotel Sherman. 3. Hotel Diller. 4. Arcade Building."

title: 1st Ave. between Cherry and Columbia St., 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Front Street 1880. East side from Cherry to Columbia." On verso:  1. Elephant Store. 2 Reinig Block. 3. C. P. Stone block--Stone's grocery. L. P. Smith & Sons, jewelers. M. D. ease, milliner. Upstairs, Charles Moore, photographer. J. S. Grasse, dentist. 4. F. W. Wald, hardware. 5. Hendrick's plumbing shop. Caption mounted under photo - 61. East side of the same street at the same time from Cherry to Columbia. Several handwritten (illegible) names.

title: Fire origin from 1st Ave. and Spring St., June 6, 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Fire. June 6, 1889. At place of origin. Front Street looking South from Spring Street.  Fire began at southwest corner of Front Street and Madison Street. Center: dome of Frye's Opera house. M. R. Maddock's building is the white building."

title: 1st Ave. south from Cherry St., 1874
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Front Street [1st Ave.]. 1874. Looking South from Cherry Street. 1. Sanders Block. 2. Vanity Fair beer hall. 3. Western Union Telegraph Office." Transcribed from back of photo: "Right: L. S. Rowe grocery. Nels Chilberg grocery. A. B. Stewart drug store. Boyd and Ponein. Center. Vanity Fair beer hall. Sanders Block. Left: Stairway to Yesler's Hall. Western Union Telegraph. W.F. Wustoff, hardware. A. W. Piper, bakery and confectionary. Trees in front of Yesler's home.  Caption on image: Seattle 1874. Front Street and Cherry."
subjects: Stewart and Holmes Drug Company (Seattle, Wash.)

title: 1st Ave. S. north from S. Washington St., 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Commercial [1st Ave. S.]. 1870. From Washington Street to Mill Street [Yesler Way]. 1. Harrington and Smith Building. 2. Pinkam clothing store. 3. City Market. 4. C. Z. Miles, stoves. 5. Pioneer drug store. 6. Frauenthal Bros. Store. 7. George Smith, butcher. 8. J. Kean, barber 9. Unidentified. 10. Robbins, liquor dealer. 11. Eureka bakery. 12. Sullivan's variety store." Transcribed from back of photo: "Right side: Sullivan's variety store. Eureka Bakery (Meydenbauer home). Robbins, wholesale and retail liquor. J. Kean, barber shop. George Smith, butcher shop. Frauenthal Bros., general merchandise. Left side: Harrington and Smith building. Pinkham clothing store."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St.

title: "Beaver" steamboat, ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Ships. Beaver (Steamer). First steamer on Puget Sound, used by Hudson's Bay Co. in coastal waters of Oregon, Washington, British Columbia and Alaska from 1836-1874. Wrecked July 26, 1888 in Burrard Inlet."

title: View north from 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St., 1878
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. 1878 looking North from Main Street. 1. Territorial University. 2. Webster house. 2. Sixth Street School. 4. Whitworth house." Transcribed from back of photograph: "University of Washington , top center. 6th Street School, below that. Whitworth home on top of hill right of school. Webster home below cupola of school."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: View from 2nd Ave. and Pike St., 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Second Avenue and Pike Street. 1870. 1. A. A. Denny house. 2. Yesler's mill and wharf. 3. Front Street. 4. Union Street."

title: First trip of Seattle Coal Company railroad, December 1871
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Transportation. First train coming in from Lake Union on Seattle's first railroad. December 25, 1871. South end of Lake Union. Tracks followed what is now Westlake Avenue."
intersection: Valley St. and Westlake Ave. N.

title: Territorial University from near 3rd Ave. and Union St., 1878
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Colleges and Universities. Washington (state) University. Territorial University. Main building. Exterior. Fourth Avenue and University Street. Built 1861-1862, demolished 1910. 1878. John Pike, Architect. Photograph taken from Third Avenue and Pike Street."

title: View south from 2nd Ave. and Pike St., 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Second Avenue and Pike Street looking South 1870."

title: Yesler Way west from 2nd Ave., 1874
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Mill Street [Yesler Way]. 1874. Looking West from Second Avenue. 1. J. S. Maggs, dentist. 2. Wisconsin house. 3. Hop Sing laundry. 4. Yesler's mill. 5. Occidental Square."

title: View from Broadway and James St., 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Broadway and James Street. 1889. Looking northeast. E. Madison is the diagonal street in the upper left corner."

title: View from 1st Ave. and Pike St., 1878.
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From First Avenue and Pike Street. 1878. Looking South. Center background--Arlington Hotel, Yesler's mill and Yesler's dock. Wreck of bark (Windward) in front of dock. M. R. Maddock's building left in front of trestle. R. H. Denny, North side of Union Street. Young Naturalist's first home, rear of A. A. Denny home."

title: Schmeig's Brewery, ca. 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Buildings. Schmeig's Brewery. Front Street [1st Ave.] and Columbia Street. Built 1865, demolished 1875. About 1870."

title: Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad Depot and Machine Shop, ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Railroad Stations. Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad Depot and Machine Shop. Built 1876?, demolished by fire June 6, 1889. First depot in Seattle. 1. Washington Iron works."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. King St.

title: Trinity Parish Church, 1874
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Churches. Trinity Parish Church. (Episcopal) Third Avenue and Jefferson Street. Built 1870-1871, demolished by fire June 6, 1889. 1874. First Episcopal church in Seattle."

title: 1st Ave. north from Marion St., 1878
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Front Street [1st Ave.] 1878. Looking North from either Madison or Marion Street. 1. M. R. Maddock's Block. 2. Charles Louch store. 3. W. H. Pumphrey house. 4. Goldsmith house. 5. Sam Eustis house. 6. Sam Kenney house. 7. Elephant store. 8. Reinig block."

title: James St. and Yesler Way, 1880
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Streets. James Street 1880. Intersection of James Street and Mill Street [Yesler Way] at Front Street [1st Ave.]. 1. Occidental Hotel. 2. Vanity Fair beer hall. 3. Frack grocery store. 4. Mackintosh and Reeves Bank. 5. Gem Saloon. 6. Gardner Kellogg drug store. 7. Daily Post building. 8. Trees of which first three were used for lynching of January 1882." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Right side: Daily Post building (1st three trees used for lynching January 18, 1882). Left side: Occidental Hotel. Vanity Fair Saloon. Frach grocery store. Mackintosh and Reeves Bank. Gem Saloon (Charlie Anderson, proprietor). Drug Store (Gard. Kellogg)"

title: Jackson St. wharf, 1882
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Waterfront. Wharves.  1882. Jackson Street wharf. City and Ocean dock. Center Right side: Bow's livery stable.  Center Right side: New England Hotel. Tower above that, City Hall. Catholic Church, with steeple. To right of that is Arlington Hotel."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and S. Jackson St.

title: View from Denny Hill, 1882
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Denny Hill, 1882. Looking South. 1. Alfred Lee Palmer house. 2. Henry G. Struve. 3. Kenyon house. 4. David Shires house. 5. J. H. Payne house. 6. John Jordan house. 7. Wilson Denny house. 8. Second Avenue. 9. Pine Street."

title: Steamer "Alida," 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Ships. Alida (Steamer). At wharf at foot of Columbia Street. 1870. Built in Seattle in 1860s. On Seattle to Victoria run, burned at Gig Harbor in 1890s. First Methodist Protestant Church (the 'Brown Church') at left."
intersection: Alaskan Way S. and Columbia St.

title: View north from 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St., 1876
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Commercial Street [1st Ave. S.]. 1876. Looking North from Main Street. 1. Yesler's Hall. 2. Masonic Hall. 3. Cosmopolitan Hotel (later Esmond Hotel)." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Left side: Edge of New England Hotel. Clancy's saloon Southeast corner of Washington and Commercial Street. R. Center Right side: Cosmopolitan Hotel (afterward Esmond House). Masonic Hall. Yesler's Hall. Building above Yesler's Hall with Gables, M.V.B. Stacy house (where First National Bank is now, 1933). L. Background--University of Washington. Central School, Third Avenue between Madison and Spring."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: Train with lumber for Columbian Exposition at Columbia St. and Alaskan Way, 1893
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Lumbering. Fir log for World's Columbian Exposition. Railroad Avenue and Columbia Street. 1893. 1. Dietrich Hamm. 2. Mr. Busby."

title: View of waterfront north from Seneca St., 1878
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Waterfront. 1878. Looking northeast from Seneca Street. Front Street parallel to water."

title: Reviewing stand decorated for visit of President Benjamin Harrison at 1st Ave. and Yesler Way, May 6, 1891
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Harrison, Benjamin. Visit. May 6, 1891. Reviewing Stand. Yesler Avenue at Front Street (looking South). 1. Olympic Block. 2. Hotel Northern. Reviewing stand in what is now Pioneer Place."

title: View north from James Street and Yesler Way, 1891
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Second Avenue. 1891. Looking North from Yesler Avenue. 1. Seattle Hotel. 2. Butler Hotel. 3. Hinckley Block."

title: Yesler's dock, 1875
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Wharves. Yesler's dock. Foot of Mill Street. 1875."

title: First car on James St. Line at 12th Ave., 1890
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Transportation. James Street line. First car. 1890. Twelfth Avenue and James Street. Car too heavy to run. G.O. Haller house at left. Power house in rear."

title: Seattle waterfront from Marion to Union, ca. 1868
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Waterfront. About 1870. between Columbia Street and University Street. 1. Occidental Brotherhood building. 2. First Methodist Protestant Church (the Brown Church)  3. Territorial University." Contrary to the photo's caption, the location actually appears to show the view from Elliott Bay between Marion St. and Union St. The white building along the water is the Occidental Brotherhood Building which was located at the base of Madison St. The First Methodist Protestant Church appears further up and to the left, followed by the Territorial University.

title: 1st Ave. south from Madison St., 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Streets. Front Street [1st Ave.]. 1880. Looking South from Madison Street. A.W. Piper and son, Walter, in foreground. 1. Occidental Brotherhood Building. 2. Schmeig's Brewery." Transcribed from back of photo: "On right side:  Occidental Brotherhood Building. Schweig's brewery (white building pointed roof). Zephyr (Steamer) on ship ways rear of brewery. Top center: roof of Arlington Hotel. Left side: A.W. Piper and Walter Piper."

title: View NE from Elliot Bay, 1878
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Views. From Elliott Bay 1878. Looking northeast from Madison Street. 1. Amos Brown dock and warehouse. 2. Williamson foundry."

title: Our Lady of Good Help Church, 1870
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Churches. Our Lady of Good Help Church (Roman Catholic). Fourth Avenue. South and Park Avenue (Washington Street). Built 1866-1870.  Enlarged 1883. 1870. First Catholic church in Seattle. Porch of Baxter house at left."
subjects: Our Lady of Good Help Catholic Church (Seattle, Wash.)
intersection: 4th Ave. S. and S. Washington St.
